 to bolster morale were taken nevertheless, in particular with regard to protection against air raids. An examination of indicative factors concludes that moral fluctuated but was in the main good, right to the end of the war. In examining this phenomenon, due credit is accorded to government policies for the maintenance of morale, but special emphasis is given to the 'invisible chain' of patriotic feeling that held the nation together during its time of trial.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aair raids.  ablack-marketeering.  acivilian morale.  adefeatism.  agovernment policies.  anation.  apanic.  apatriotic feeling.  aration-cheating.  atotal war.1 aMackay, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137425zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137425zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137425/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA